{"key":"post-9945785","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9945785</id>\n<content>Bulk substrates are substances we spawn our fully colonized rye grains or cakes into, in order to increase the size of the medium.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Casing layers are non-nutritious layers, usually of peat/verm that are placed over he top of the substrate, when used.&amp;nbsp;  When growing cubensis using bulk substrates, a casing layer is not required.&amp;nbsp; Manure and straw fruit as well or sometimes better when left uncased, provided you maintain proper conditions.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Some growers layer the spawn with the bulk substrate and others mix it thoroughly.&amp;nbsp; I prefer to layer, but try it both ways.&amp;nbsp; Pasteurize bulk substrates for an hour at 60C to 70C, measured at the center of the substrate.&amp;nbsp;  Coffee grinds and coir are a good example of a bulk substrate.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9945819</next>\n<prev>9945748</prev>\n<first>9945748</first>\n<last>9946217</last>\n<when>1236712966</when>\n<utime>03/10/09 10:22 PM</utime>\n</post>"}